The [US overdose deaths data](https://data.cdc.gov/National-Center-for-Health-Statistics/VSRR-Provisional-Drug-Overdose-Death-Counts/xkb8-kh2a/about_data){target="_blank"} analyzed in this report were acquired from the National Vital Statistics System (NVSS) and downloaded as a `.csv` file. For every month from January 2015 to October 2025, this dataset captured the number of deaths in US jurisdictions due to drug overdose that occurred in the 12-month period ending in the month indicated. For example, the reported count of January 2015 for a given US jurisdiction represents the reported number of overdose deaths from January 2014 to January 2015.

```{r, echo = FALSE}
drug_deaths <- read.csv("VSRR_Provisional_Drug_Overdose_Death_Counts.csv")

drug_deaths_preview <- drug_deaths[c(74231, 30021), ] %>% 
  as.tibble()

knitr::kable(head(drug_deaths_preview, 2), caption = "Preview of Raw NVSS Dataset")
```

```{r, echo = FALSE, output = FALSE}

drug_deaths <- drug_deaths %>% 
  select(c(1:6, 9)) %>% 
  mutate(Deaths = as.numeric(parse_number(Data.Value)),
         Date = my(paste(Month, Year, sep = ",")),
         State.Abb = State,
         State = State.Name) %>% 
  relocate(Month, .before = Year) %>% 
  relocate(Date, .after = Year) %>% 
  relocate(Deaths, .after = Indicator) %>% 
  relocate(State.Abb, .before = State)
drug_deaths$Data.Value <- NULL
drug_deaths$State.Name <- NULL

# Remove "Period" column because all values are the same
# table(drug_deaths$Period)
drug_deaths$Period <- NULL

# Look at "State.Name": Notice District of Columbia, Puerto Rico, United States, and New York City
table(drug_deaths$State) %>% 
  as.data.frame()

# The total death count for the United States does not include deaths occurring in Puerto Rico.
drug_deaths <- drug_deaths %>% 
  filter(!State == "Puerto Rico")

# Combine New York City and New York together:
new_york <- drug_deaths %>% 
  filter(State == "New York" | State == "New York City")
new_york$State <- NULL

new_york <- new_york %>% pivot_wider(names_from = State.Abb,
                                      values_from = Deaths) %>%
  mutate(Deaths = NY + YC)
new_york <- new_york %>% 
  select(Month, Year, Date, Indicator, Deaths) %>% 
  mutate(State.Abb = rep("NY", dim(new_york)[1]),
         State = rep("New York", dim(new_york)[1])) %>% 
  relocate(c(State.Abb, State), .before = Month) 

# Add in "New York" (state) values back to dataset
drug_deaths <- drug_deaths %>% 
  filter(State != "New York") %>% 
    filter(State != "New York City") 
drug_deaths <- rbind(drug_deaths, new_york)
```

To begin clean the data, the `Period`, `Percent.Pending.Investigation`, `Footnote`, `Foot.Symbol`, and `Predicted.Values` columns were removed. A `Date` variable was added to concatenate the month and year data. After inspecting the `State` categories, it was decided to filter out *Puerto Rico* data. Furthermore, data for *New York City* and *New York* were combined into one unified jurisdiction, *New York*.

As previously mentioned, this dataset captures the monthly incident overdose deaths caused by many different classes of drugs, which are captured under the `Indicator` variable.

```{r preview_indicators, echo = FALSE}
indicators <- unique(drug_deaths$Indicator) %>% 
  as.data.frame()

colnames(indicators) <- c("Causes of Overdose Death")

knitr::kable(indicators, caption = "Causes of Overdose Deaths captured in the NVSS Dataset")
```

Given the goals of this this analysis to study drug overdose and opioid overdose death trends, the `Indicators` column was filtered to four categories that captured incident numbers of overdose deaths related to different opioid classes:

1.  *Heroin (T40.1)*
2.  *Natural & semi-synthetic opioids (T40.2)*
3.  *Synthetic opioids, excl. methadone (T40.4)*
4.  *Number of Drug Overdose Deaths* \[comparison group\]

Of important note, category #3, *Synthetic opioids, excl. methadone,* classifies overdose deaths attributed to fentanyl and its derivatives. This is the class of opioids tied to the "third wave" of the US opioid overdose crisis and will be of particular interest to this analysis.

```{r indicators, echo = FALSE}

# Filter to indicators of interest
drug_deaths <- drug_deaths %>% 
  filter(Indicator == "Heroin (T40.1)" | 
           Indicator == "Methadone (T40.3)" |
           Indicator == "Number of Drug Overdose Deaths" |
           Indicator == "Natural & semi-synthetic opioids (T40.2)" |
           Indicator == "Synthetic opioids, excl. methadone (T40.4)") %>% 
  mutate(Indicator = case_when(
    Indicator == "Heroin (T40.1)" ~ "Heroin",
    Indicator == "Methadone (T40.3)" ~ "Methadone",
    Indicator == "Number of Drug Overdose Deaths" ~ "Drug.Overdose",
    Indicator == "Natural & semi-synthetic opioids (T40.2)" ~ "Natural.SemiSynthetic",
    TRUE ~ "Synthetic"
  ))

drug_deaths$Indicator <- with(drug_deaths, 
                              factor(Indicator, 
                                     levels = c("Heroin", "Natural.SemiSynthetic",
                                                "Methadone", "Synthetic",
                                                "Drug.Overdose")))

drug_deaths <- drug_deaths %>% 
  pivot_wider(names_from = Indicator,
              values_from = Deaths)

```

Next, for the state-level analysis to be normalized by population, US yearly census data was added to the NVSS dataset. These population data were acquired from United States Census Bureau ([2010-2020](https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/popest/technical-documentation/research/evaluation-estimates/2020-evaluation-estimates/2010s-state-total.html){target="_blank"}, [2020-2025](https://www.census.gov/data/tables/time-series/demo/popest/2020s-state-total.html){target="_blank"}) and downloaded as `.xlsx` files.

After cleaning the population data, it was attatched to the NVSS table. Two additional columns, `drugdeathper100k` and `syntheticdeathper100k` were created to capture the number of deaths per 100,000 in the population from *all drug overdoses* and *synthetic opioid overdosees*, respectively.

```{r, message = FALSE, echo = FALSE}
# Population of 2010s
pop_2010s <- readxl::read_xlsx("pop_2010.xlsx")
pop_2010s <- pop_2010s %>% select(-2)
colnames(pop_2010s) <- c("State", seq(2010, 2020, 1))
pop_2010s <- pop_2010s[-c(1:3, 5:8, 60:67),]
pop_2010s$State <- gsub("\\.", "", pop_2010s$State)
pop_2010s <- pop_2010s %>% 
  mutate(across(`2010`:`2020`, as.numeric)) %>% 
  pivot_longer(cols = `2010`:`2020`,
    names_to = "Year",
    values_to = "Population")

# Population of 2020s
pop_2020s <- readxl::read_xlsx("pop_2020.xlsx")
pop_2020s <- pop_2020s %>% select(-c(2:3))
colnames(pop_2020s) <- c("State", seq(2021, 2025, 1))
pop_2020s <- pop_2020s[-c(1:3, 5:8, 60:67),]
pop_2020s$State <- gsub("\\.", "", pop_2020s$State)
pop_2020s <- pop_2020s %>% 
  mutate(across(`2021`:`2025`, as.numeric)) %>% 
  pivot_longer(cols = `2021`:`2025`,
    names_to = "Year",
    values_to = "Population")

pop <- rbind(pop_2010s, pop_2020s) %>% 
  mutate(Year = as.numeric(Year))

# Adding Population to drug_deaths
drug_deaths <- left_join(drug_deaths, pop, 
          by = c("State", "Year"))

# Creating "drugdeathper100k"
drug_deaths <- drug_deaths %>% 
  mutate(drugdeathper100k = round((Drug.Overdose/Population)*100000)) %>% 
  mutate(syntheticdeathper100k = round((Synthetic/Population)*100000))

```

Finally, the NVSS dataset was filtered into two separate data sets based on the `State` variable, to separate US vs state-level data.

```{r, echo = FALSE}
# Split into National vs State-Level Datasets
drug_deaths_nat <- drug_deaths %>% filter(State.Abb == "US")
drug_deaths_state <- drug_deaths %>% filter(State.Abb != "US")
```

```{r, echo=FALSE}
as.data.frame(head(drug_deaths_nat, 3)) %>% 
  knitr::kable(caption = "Preview of Cleaned NVSS Dataset for US Data")

as.data.frame(drug_deaths_state[c(6126, 6576, 2074), ]) %>% 
  knitr::kable(caption = "Preview of Cleaned NVSS Dataset for State-Level Data")
```

