Comparing January 2015 to January 2023 data, the District of Columbia, Vermont, and Maine saw the largest percent increases in 12 month-ending drug overdose deaths per 100,000 (394%, 242%, and 219%, respectively). All states other than Utah saw percent increases in deaths. The minimum, mean, and maximum of the percent changes per 100,000 were -9.5%, 117%, and 394%. Overall, the percent increases of 12 month-ending drug overdose deaths in US states during this timeframe are also much larger in magnitude than those seen comparing January 2015 to October 2025 data in Table 1.

When comparing January 2023 to October 2025 data, the opposite trend is seen: a majority of states experienced percent decreases in 12 month-ending drug overdose deaths per 100,000. North Carolina and Rhode Island saw the greatest decreases in magnitude, with -59% and -55%, respectively. Notably, Vermont experienced the 7th greatest decrease in magnitude (-51%). The minimum, mean, and maximum of the percent changes per 100,000 were -59%, -33%, and 19%.

### State Specific Trends

To more closely hone-in on distinct state trends, this section will focus on the unique drug overdose death trends of three states identified from the [State-Level Trend Results](report.qmd#state-level-trends-1){target="_blank"}:

1.  **District of Columbia**: The District of Columbia saw the highest reported count of 12 month-ending drug overdose deaths per 100,000 among any US state across the decade \[Figure 2\]. This district also experienced the greatest percent increase in 12 month-ending drug overdose deaths per 100,000, comparing January 2015 to January 2023 \[Table 2\].

2.  **Washington**: Washington saw the greatest percent increase in 12 month-ending drug overdose deaths per 100,000 between January 2015 and October 2025 \[Table 1\]. Furthermore, it was one of only five states to still see a percent increase in 12 month-ending overdose deaths per 100,000 between January 2023 and October 2025 \[Table 2\].

3.  **Vermont**: Vermont experienced the second-highest percent increase in 12 month-ending overdose deaths per 100,000 between January 2015 and January 2023 \[Table 2\]. However, it also experienced the seventh greatest percent decrease in 12 month-ending overdose deaths per 100,000 between January 2023 and October 2025 \[Table 2\].

<center>

